history.provenance: Previously no. 122 in the collection of Nils Reinhold Brocman, book collector and librarian at the Royal Library and Antiquities Archive. Upon his death in 1770, a large part of his book collection was donated to the Antiquities Archive (SBL).
history.acquisition: Transferred to the National Library from the Antiquities Archive.

msItem.title: Proper of time
msItem.rubric: Dominica prima aduentus domini cum ceteris capitulum
msItem.explicit: hic vere propheta qui venturus est in mundum (John 6:14) psalmus magnificat et cetera

note.p:
The Proper of time begins with the First Sunday of Advent and ends with the Twenty-fifth Sunday after Trinity. After this, the collect for the Twenthy-sixth Sunday after Trinity, along with an instruction for the 22-27 Sundays after Trinity, is added by a different medieval hand (). In the lower margin of , an early modern hand has made a note comparing the addition to the contents of the printed edition of 1496 : NB In impresso non extat Dominica XXVI sed eius loco
.

msItem.title: Proper of saints
msItem.incipit: In illo tempore Stabat iohannes et ex discipulis eius duo (John 1:35)

note.p: The Proper of saints begins with the vigil of St Andrew (29 Nov.). After the feast of St Katherine (25 Nov.) follow the feasts of St Clement (23 Nov.), St Theodore (9 Nov.), and St Martin (10 Nov.).
In the process of rebinding, the bifolium making up /has been misplaced; it should come after the bifolium making up /.
consists of a small paper note which has been inserted into the manuscript. The recto transmits an excerpt from the life of St Ignatius.

supportDesc.condition: The manuscript has been rebound and the edges trimmed. In the process of rebinding, the bifolium making up / has been misplaced; this bifolium should follow after /. Several edges and corners have been repaired with paper strips. Half of has been torn off and the remaining half replaced with a paper strip.

handDesc.p: The main text is written in one or two different hands; the identification of these is tentative. The smaller additions to the text are written in two or three separate hands (hand 3 and 5 possibly the same).
handDesc.handNote: Gothic cursive with the occasional occurrence of unlooped ascenders.
Gothic cursive with the occasional occurrence of unlooped ascenders.

p.note: Marginal annotations in at least two different hands - one of which appears to be identical to the main scribe - of additions of items, corrections, and instructions. In several places, the text of the additions has been lost due to trimming.
Notes in black ink by early modern hand recording differences from the printed edition of 1496 .
Top of page, occasional annotations in a modern or early modern hand, noting the office / saint in question (: Pars secunda).
